Name: Geneva Perserve
Notes: This preserve, part of the Lake Whatcom Watershed Forestland, is undeveloped and managed for watershed protection but is open to the public.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: East Acme Farm
Notes: This land is currently undeveloped but is open to the public. It is the proposed site a future trailhead.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Riverstead
Notes: This land is undeveloped and is managed for farming, fish and wildlife habit but it is open to the public. There is a pullout by the gate.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Catalyst
Notes: This land is undeveloped and managed for salmon restoration and conservation but it is open to the public. There is a pullout by the gate.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: South Fork Chinook - Roos
Notes: This land is undeveloped and managed for conservation but it is open to the public. Access is through the adjoining Catalyst conservation property or from the river.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Lake Whatcom Waterfront
Notes: This undeveloped property is open for public recreation.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Nesset Farm
Notes: This historic homstead is managed for consrvation. Access, although currently undeveloped, is via the Overby Trail.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Port Blakely
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. Thre are pullouts on Saxon road that provides access to the property.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Olsen Estate
Details: Parking: Parking for 30 cars at trailhead.
Notes: This park provides access to the Lookout Mountain Trail. Dogs are allowed on the trail.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: White Deer
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation and restoration. It is open to the public but has not facilities. There is a pullout by the gate.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Overby Farmstead
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Saxon Riparian
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation of salmon, eagles and elk but is open to the public. The only access is from the river, please do not try to reach this area across the adjacent private properties.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Bajema
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation of salmon, eagles and elk but is open to the public. The only access is from the river, please do not try to reach this area across the adjacent private properties.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Bayes
Notes: This undeveloped urban wetland habitat along the interurban trailis managed for conservation but is open to the public.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Racehorse Creek
Notes: This undeveloped area is managed for conservation. It provides access to the North Fork of the Nooksack River and has forest roads crossing it.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: North Fork Island
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. The only access is from theNorth Fork Nooksack River, please do not try to reach this area across the adjacent private properties.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: North Fork Eagle
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. There is limited pullout parking by the gate and a short loop trail to the river.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: North Fork Eagle - Miller
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation of salmon, eagle and elk, but is open to the public. There is a pullout by the gate.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Bottiger's Pond
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for convervation of North Fork Nooksack riparian areas and wetlands and Bottiger's Pond. It is open to the public but has no facilities.  There is a pullout by the gate.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Craver
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. There is a pullout along the road.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Nooksack River Conservation Area
Notes: These undeveloped properties are managed for conservation but are open to the public. Access is from the Nooksack River or from the two points where the conservation area touches Truck Rd. Please do not cross private property to access these lands.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Little Bear Hollow
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. The only access is from theNooksack River, please do not try to reach this area across the adjacent private properties.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Wildcat Reach - Steiner I and II
Name_: Wildcat Reach - Steiner I and II
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation. Access is from a pullout by the highway.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Glacier Springs & Canyon Creek
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed to help conserve salmon habitat but is open to public. Accesss is from a gate on the highway. There is a pullout for parking.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Mt Baker Baptist & Pitts Sportsman
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed to help conserve salmon habitat but is open to public. The property can be accessed from the Bay to Baker Trail.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Northwest Baptist Convention
Notes: This undeveloped land that straddles the North Fork Nooksack River is managed for conservation but is open to the public. The only access is from the river, please do not try to reach this area across the adjacent private properties.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Harrison / Kendall Creek Wetlands
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. It can be accessed from Eason Rd but there is no nearby parking.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Heath Middle Fork & Schuman Granger
Notes: This undeveloped land with salmon, eagle and elk habitat is managed for conservation but is open to the public. The only access is from the Middle Fork Nooskack River. Please do not try to reach this area across the adjacent private properties.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Hutchinson Creek
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. It can be accessed from the WDNR forest land surrounding it.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Wickersham Forest
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Samish River Tributary and Wetlands
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. There are pullouts where you can park at several gates along Innis Creek Road.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Ladies of the Lake
Notes: This undeveloped land is managed for conservation but is open to the public. You can park at a pullout on South Bay Drive.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Marlowe Urban Wetland
Notes: This undeveloped urban wetland habitat along the Interurban Trail is managed for conservation but is open to the public.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Paulus
Notes: This undeveloped urban wetland habitat along the Interurban Trail is managed for conservation but is open to the public. It adjoins the Sehome Hill Arboretum.
Source: Location contributed by Whatcom Land Trust

Name: Point Doughty Natural Area Preserve

Notes: This island preserve protects natural examples of rain shadow vegetation. Bald eagles nest on the preserve and seals haul out on the rocky shoreline.  A small recreation site on the point is used for marine mammal study, kayak and small boat camping.

Name: Cattle Point Natural Resource Conservation Area
Name_: Cattle Point Natural Resource Conservation Area
Amenities: Amenities: Bathroom, Day-Use Area, Education Program, Picnic Tables
Features: Features: Beach, Historic Site, Interpretive Signs
Notes: Public access to this area, made up of two parcels, includes several parking spaces at the interpretive center, which includes a public restroom, beach access, and short trail along the bluff above San Juan Channel with panoramic views to the east.

Name: Cypress Island NRCA & NAP
Facilities: Facilites: Drift Boat or Kayak Launch, Mooring Buoy, Trails
Notes: This relatively undeveloped island offers a scenic reminder of conditions in Western Washington prior to European settlement.  It is a popular destination for boaters, offering recreation opportunities, scenic viewpoints, lakes, and miles of trails.

Name: Table Mountain Natural Resource Conservation Area
Name_: Table Mountain Natural Resource Conservation Area
Details: 5 miles of trails; Parking: Parking off site
Notes: This conservation area provides contains relatively undisturbed examples of upland and wetland forests, mountain meadows, and rare plant populations. It is a good destination for seasoned hikers, with rugged and challenging trails.

Name: Morning Star Natural Resource Conservation Area
Name_: Morning Star Natural Resource Conservation Area
Details: Dispersed Camping; 25 miles of trails; Parking: There are three parking areas
Notes: The area's steep topography offers expansive views of Spada Lake, the Puget lowlands and the Cascade Mountains. Several trails in the Mount Pilchuck, and Greider Ridge areas provide access to forests, prominent ridges, subalpine meadows and lakes.

Name: Dishman Hills Natural Resource Conservation Area
Name_: Dishman Hills Natural Resource Conservation Area
Notes: This site is notable for dramatically sculpted terrain left by the floods which issued from Glacial Lake Missoula. It has an enviornmental education viewing platform and trails that connect to a larger trail system.

Name: Woodward Bay Natural Resource Conservation Area
Name_: Woodward Bay Natural Resource Conservation Area
Features: Features: Historic Site, Interpretive Signs, Ocean Access
Notes: With an interpretive center, three hiking trails and interpretive signs, this wildlife sanctuary is a popular destination for environmental education. It protects habitat ranging from marine shoreline and wetlands to mature second growth forest.

Name: Lake Louise Natural Resource Conservation Area
Name_: Lake Louise Natural Resource Conservation Area
Details: Parking: Parking at the Stimpson Family Nature Reserve
Notes: This NRCA and the adjacent Stimson Family Nature Reserve offer more than 4 miles of hiking trails with interpretive signs. The landscape includes bogs and wetlands, with an active beaver pond, and hardwood thickets and stands of Douglas fir.

Name: Camas Meadows Natural Area Preserve
Notes: This preserve with lush meadows, aspen groves, and ponderosa pine and fir forests, contains the largest known population of two endangered plant species. A primitive, informal trail leads from a small parking area near the entrance.

Name: Chehalis River Surge Plain Natural Area Preserve
Name_: Chehalis River Surge Plain Natural Area Preserve
Details: Hand Launch; Parking: Three small parking lots.
Notes: This natural area preserve has a .5 mile ADA accessible trail leading to an observation platform. The interpretive trail continues for another 3 miles along Blue Slough. It also has water access points at Preacher's Slough and Blue Slough Rd.

Name: Columbia Hills Natural Area Preserve
Notes: Visitors can enjoy this Natural Area Preserve walking up a primitive road that climbs to the ridge top through fields of wildflowers. The trail provides stunning views of the surrounding country side. There is a short interpretive trail.

Name: Selah Cliffs Natural Area Preserve
Notes: Selah Cliffs is situated in a landscape of bedrock and talus formed from the approximately 12 million year old Pomona basalt flow. Other features include the rocky floodplain of Selah Creek and areas of shrub-steppe habitat.

Name: Dragoon Creek
Notes: This campground boasts developed campsites with RV access.   A small open field used for day use is adjacent to Dragoon Creek, which flows through the middle of the campground. Pets are allowed on leash

Name: Griffin Bay Campground
Notes: This five-campsite campground on San Juan Island provides stunning ocean views.

Name: Columbia National Wildlife Refuge
Sports: Summer Sports: Fishing, Hiking, Hunting, Kayaking
Notes: Formed by fire, ice, floods and volcanic tempest, carved by periods of extreme violence of natural forces, the refuge lies in the middle of the Drumheller Channeled Scablands of central Washington.

Name: Conboy Lake National Wildlife Refuge
Sports: Summer Sports: Fishing, Hiking, Hunting; Winter Sports: Cross Country Skiing, Snowshoeing
Notes: This Refuge,  encompasses over 6,500 acres of the historic Conboy/Camas lakebeds, a shallow marshy wetland area drained by early settlers. Much of the area is closed to the public but there are areas open for recreation.

Name: Dungeness National Wildlife Refuge
Hours: Hours: Daily 7 am to half and hour before sunset.
Features: Features: Beach, Bird Watching, Historic Site, Interpretive Signs, Wildlife Viewing
Notes: At Dungeness Refuge, one of the world's longest natural sand spits softens the rough sea waves to form a quiet bay and harbor, gravel beaches, and tideflats.

Name: Flattery Rocks National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: This Refuge consists of a portion of 870 islands, rocks, and reefs extending for more than 100 miles along Washington's Pacific coast. They are closed to the public to protect seabird nesting sites but can be viewed from the coastal roads or beaches.

Name: Franz Lake National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: This refuge in the Columbia River Gorge National Scenic Area provides a variety of habitats. It is closed to the public but can be viewed from an observation platform.

Name: Grays Harbor National Wildlife Refuge
Hours: Hours: The refuge trail is open from sunrise to sunset.
Features: Features: Accessible Facilities, Bird Watching, Boardwalk, Interpretive Signs
Details: Parking: Limited parking is available across from Lana's Hangar Cafe on Airport Way. Do not park on the black
Notes: Access to this refuge is restricted to an accessible boardwalk with interpretive signs. The refuge, within the Grays Harbor Estuary, is one of the four major staging areas of migrating shorebirds in the Pacific Flyway.

Name: Julia Butler Hansen Refuge for the Columbian White-Tailed Deer
Name_: Julia Butler Hansen Refuge for the Columbian White-Tailed Deer
Hours: Hours: Daylight hours only. Hunters can enter the refuge up to 1.5 hours prior to legal hunting times.
Features: Features: Interpretive Signs, Ocean Access, Wildlife Viewing
Notes: Julia Butler Hansen Refuge for the Columbian White-tailed Deer is rich in wildlife. Thousands of people come to the refuge each year to enjoy solitude, to commune with nature, and to share the joys of wildlife with family and friends.

Name: Lewis and Clark National Wildlife Refuge
Name_: Lewis and Clark National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: This refuge includes approximately 20 islands stretching over 27 miles of the Columbia River. Although seldom visited by humans, people following in Lewis and Clark's footsteps or paddles are discovering this little-known refuge.

Name: Little Pend Oreille National Wildlife Refuge
Name_: Little Pend Oreille National Wildlife Refuge
Sports: Summer Sports: Camping, Fishing, Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting, Mountain Biking; Winter Sports: Cross Country Skiing, Snowshoeing
Notes: Hidden between the foothills of the Cascades and the Rocky Mountains, this unique, forested, mountainous Refuge provides habitat for large mammals and migratory song birds. Three entrances are open year-round, the others are closed January 1-April 14.

Name: McNary National Wildlife Refuge
Sports: Summer Sports: Boating, Fishing, Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting, Kayaking
Notes: Few areas in North America support waterfowl populations in the extraordinary numbers found within McNary National Wildlife Refuge. Visitors enjoy spectacular concentrations of Canada geese, mallards, and other waterfowl.

Name: Pierce National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: Closed to visitors, this small refuge has big impacts on wildlife. It supports one of the last remaining runs of chum salmon on the Columbia River and is also home to other State threatened and endangered species.

Name: Protection Island National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: In order to protect this fragile habitat the Refuge is closed to visitation. It can be viewed by boat, but a 200 yard off-shore buffer is enforced to ensure adult birds are not flushed from their nests.

Name: Quillayute Needles National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: One of the first National Wildlife Refuges, this area was set aside to enhance habitat for struggling seabird populations. A 200-yard buffer zone surrounds each island to protect the wildlife, but they can be viewed from several beaches on the coast.

Name: Ridgefield National Wildlife Refuge
Features: Features: Bird Watching, Historic Site, Interpretive Signs, Lake Access, Wildlife Viewing
Notes: The Ridgefield National Wildlife Refuge was established in 1965 to provide wintering habitat for the dusky subspecies of the Canada goose.  Today, the Refuge preserves both habitat for wildlife, and evidence of the people who once lived here.

Name: Saddle Mountain National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: Saddle Mountain National Wildlife Refuge lies within Washington's arid half. The shrub-steppe community it represents is one of only two large blocks of this habitat remaining in the state. It is not currently open to the public.

Name: San Juan Islands National Wildlife Refuge
Name_: San Juan Islands National Wildlife Refuge
Sports: Summer Sports: Boating, Camping, Hiking, Kayaking
Notes: This refuge of 83 rocks, reefs and islands, was set aside to protect colonies of nesting seabirds. Wildlife observation, study, and photography are allowed on Matia and Turn islands. The other islands are closed to the public.

Name: Steigerwald Lake National Wildlife Refuge
Notes: This refuge supports breeding and migrating birds. Visitors may enjoy viewing refuge wildlife and scenes of the Columbia River by accessing the Columbia River Dike Trail. Refuge lands off the dike trail are not open to the public

Name: Chopaka Mountain Wilderness Study Area
Sports: Summer Sports: Boating, Camping, Fishing, Hiking
Notes: This 5,518 acre Wilderness Study Area sits in the scenip Chopaka Mountains. . Hike or boat-in camping is also allowed in the WSA, but there are no developed campsites other than one small camping area at Chopaka Lake.

Name: Juniper Dunes Wilderness Area
Sports: Summer Sports: Camping, Hiking, Horseback Riding
Notes: This large dune system contains some of the largest sand dunes in the state. The wilderness portion of the dunes is fenced. Pack in drinking water and be prepared for extreme temperature swings. There is no surface water in the wilderness area.

Name: Juniper Dunes OHV Area and ACEC
Name_: Juniper Dunes OHV Area and ACEC
Sports: Summer Sports: Camping, Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting, OHVing
Notes: TThis large dune system contains some of the largest sand dunes in the state. It is divided into an area where OHV are permited off-road and an Area of Critical Enviornmental Concern where motorized travel is limited to existing routes/no off road travel

Name: Palmer Mountain Recreation Area
Sports: Summer Sports: Boating, Camping, Fishing, Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting, Kayaking
Notes: This is a great place to get away from it all. The autumn is especially picturesque when the many stands of aspen create a brilliant background. Enjoy the scenic views of the Okanogan hillside or the peaceful waters of Washburn Lake.

Name: Rock Creek Recreation Area
Sports: Summer Sports: Camping, Fishing, Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting, Mountain Biking
Notes: The Channeled Scablands that make up this unique environment were formed approximately 12,000 years ago by the Great Missoula floods. Escure Ranch was a working farm from the 1930s to the 1980s. The old ranch has 2 stock corrals and a camping area.

Name: BLM Lands
Location: Adams, Asotin, Benton, Chelan, Clallam, Clark, Columbia, Cowlitz, Douglas, Ferry, Franklin, Garfield, Grant, Grays Harbor, Island, Jefferson, King, Kittitas, Klickitat, Lewis, Lincoln, Mason, Okanogan, Pacific, Pend Oreille, Pierce, San Juan, Skagit, Ska
Notes: All BLM lands are open to recreation - although some are also leased for other uses. Some BLM lands are within designated areas, others are simply part fo the BLM system.

Name: Cattle Point
Features: Features: Beach, Interpretive Signs, No Motorized Use, Ocean Access
Details: Parking: Parking is limited. Visitors can park at the adjacent DNR site with a Discover Pass.
Notes: This day use area has a historic lighthouse and spectacular views of nearby islands, the Olympic Mountains and the Salish Sea. It can be crowded during the summer but visitors can enjoy a more isolated experience during the shoulder seasons.

Name: Fishtrap Recreation Area
Sports: Summer Sports: Boating, Camping, Fishing, Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting
Notes: This 7,000 acre recreation area has various habitat types from forest, shrub, grassland, wetlands and lakes. These areas are home to a wide variety of wildlife along with beautiful landscapes and even an old farmstead.

Name: Iceberg Point
Sports: Summer Sports: Boating, Fishing, Hiking, Swimming

Name: Telford Recreation Area
Sports: Summer Sports: Hiking, Horseback Riding, Hunting

Name: Yakima River Canyon Recreation Area

Notes: This area, part of the Channeled Scablands carved by the Great Missoula Floods, is managed for its recreational opportunities, wildlife habitat, and seasonal livestock grazing.

Name: Tieton River Canyon Preserve
Notes: The Tieton River Canyon is a unique place, where basalt cliffs meet oak trees, elk mingle with bighorn sheep, and rattlesnakes slither between flowers while golden eagles soar above the pines.
Source: Location contributed by The Nature Conservancy

Name: Yellow Island Preserve
Notes: Yellow Island is among the most colorful of The Nature Conservancy's preserves, long known to passengers aboard Washington's San Juan Islands ferries for its dramatic wildflower displays.

Name: Big Creek Conservancy Area
Notes: This area, protected by Forterra, consists of 262 acres of critical salmon habitat.  It is currently managed for conservancy purposes and is not open to public recreation.

Name: Cedar River Estuary
Notes: This area, protected by Forterra, consists of 166 acres of outstanding habitat to consolidate the Cedar River estuarine ecosystem.  It is currently managed for conservancy purposes and is not open to public recreation.

Name: Denny Creek MacDonald Memorial Preserve
